      <details>
        <summary>Abstract</summary>
        <article class=" has-text-justified"> Organizational Productivity is a measure of the quantity and quality of
          work done, considering
          the cost of the resources used. Various researchers have identified the most significant
          practices that is effectively practiced service sectors but little attempt has been paid to
          investigate the effects of performance appraisal practices such as rewards and recognition,
          employee feedback and employee training on organizational productivity. The broad objective
          of this study is to determine the impact of performance appraisal on organizational productivity
          among non-academic staff of College of Health Sciences and Technology Ijero-Ekiti, Ekiti-State.
          The data was collected from 100 respondents out of the population of 300 using simple random
          sampling technique with the aid of five-point Likert scale close-ended questionnaire distributed
          to non-academic staff of College of Health Science and Technology, Ijero-Ekiti. Data collected
          were analyzed through the adoption of simple percentage and regression (Statistical Package
          for Social Sciences) at 5% level of significance. The result revealed that out of the three (3)
          independent variables tested in the course of this research work, reward and recognition proxy
          was found to have most significant impact on the productivity of non-academic staff of College
          of Health Science and Technology, Ijero-Ekiti as it has the highest beta value followed by
          employee feedback, while employee training has an inverse relationship respectively. The study
          concludes that if institutions can also review the human resource management functions
          periodically, it will boost the organizational productivity.</article>
