          services, information and communication technology (ICT), electricity, water supply, sewage
          and waste management. Correlation and ordinary least square (OLS) regression analyses were
          used to determine the nature and strength of association of the variables as well as the effect
          of the explanatory variables on the dependent variable, Gross domestic product (GDP). All
          explanatory variables, except rail transport, were positively associated with GDP. Rail transport
          was negatively and moderately linked with GDP. Other explanatory variables have strong
          association with GDP except for water transport, which has a positive but weak link with GDP.
          Furthermore, the result of OLS shows that all explanatory variables were statistically significant
          in explaining the variation in output. Though rail transport, water transport, electricity as well as
          post and courier services inversely influence output, other explanatory variables positively
          influence output. Road transport positively affects output at 5% level of significance, while rail
          transport negatively influence output at 10% level of significance. Water transport, ICT, water
          supply, sewage and management affect output at 1% level of significance. The result further
          suggests that a lot of public expenditure is still needed to upgrade infrastructure, particularly
          rail transport, electricity and water transport in Nigeria.</article>
