        applicable for Nigeria?</summary>
      <hr>
      <h3>
        Authors: Modupe Mary FASORANTI,
        Saheed Aliu ALADEJANA </h3>
      <hr>
      <h3>
        Page Number: 90 - 97
      </h3>
      <hr>
      <h3>
        Key Words: Financial development, Income-inequality, Greenwood and
        Jovanovic Hypothesis
      </h3>
      <hr>
      <details>
        <summary>Abstract</summary>
        <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> Financial development does make credit cheaper for investors and
          small-scale entrepreneurs. It
          enables entrepreneurs to generate jobs and enhance the welfare of the poor. Findings from
          existing studies on the relationship between financial development and income inequality are
          inconclusive. Thus, this study tested applicability of Greenwood and Jovanovic Hypothesis to
          Nigeria. The study used time-series data from the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) Statistical
          Bulletin and National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) from 1980 to 2014. This study employed
          Dynamic Ordinary Least Square (DOLS) method to examine the effect(s) of financial
          development on income inequality in Nigeria. The results showed a positive relationship
          between income-inequality and financial development variables; hence, supporting the
          inequality-widening hypothesis. This implied that a one percent (1%) increase in financial
          development, will bring about two percent (2%), rise in income inequality in Nigeria. A plausible
          reason for this might be a mal-distribution of the fruits of economic growth. The implication of
          this finding is that improving access to finance may not reduce inequality and benefit low-
          income households in Nigeria. Income differences between high-income members of
          intermediary coalitions and low-income outsiders will widen, resulting in an increase in income-
          inequality. The study also found support for the Greenwood and Jovanovic Hypothesis which
          suggests that improving access to finance may, initially, worsen income-inequality but improve
          only after the country has reached a defining stage of financial development. The study
          concluded that income inequality is strongly influenced by financial development in Nigeria. The
          study, therefore, recommended the need to further improve the organized financial sector
          through innovations, constant and effective regulation and supervision, efficient mobilization of
          necessary funds, and making such funds available for productive investments towards reducing
          income-inequality in Nigeria.</article>
      </details>
